You have to print this with the same settings like the original.

description.text:
I designed this universal joint from scratch, with the idea to use it in the shoulder / hip joints of a robot dog I´m working on. (I hope I upload that soon too).

My main motivation was to get a universal joint with two DoF in one place, since that is what we mammals have in out shoulders and hip.

You'll see the design steps I wen though to get to were I am now. It is designed to fit the Tower Pro 9g micro servos

I know the print quality is not the best, sorry for that. The parts were printed with a cheap plastic (that looks like never ends!)

I'll upload new pictures as soon as I print with another (better) PLA.

Supports:

No

Notes:

You'll need to print:

  • 2 Arch
  • 2 Axis
  • 1 Core

Assemble instructions

To assemble this Servo based universal joint you should follow this steps:

  1. Get two servo horns and cut them to fit into the core of the joint.
  2. Attach the cut servo horns to the core using the servo screws (you'll need to make the hole a little bigger, but that can be done just screwing the screw)
  3. Place the core into the first arch
  4. Put the first servo into its place in the first arch
  5. screw the servo horn into the servo, through the opossit hole in the core
  6. Do that same thing (steps 3 to 5) with the second arch and servo

description.text:
My first upload. Very simple, I know. This is an adapter plate for the bottom of a Casio XJ-A140V slim projector for mounting to a tripod with a standard 1/4-20 thread. This makes it easier to place a projector for when a desk or table is not handy. Perfect for Halloween or outdoor parties for mounting and aiming. The 10mm hole for the brass insert is for these inserts: https://www.ebay.com/p/36pc-Brass-Assorted-Threaded-Insert-Set-Furniture-Cabinets-Assortment-Inserts/1100092849

I used a soldering iron, set to 400°F to heat up the insert and then carefully screw it in. Once cooled, it will not back out on you.

I have students build pretty complex circuits with these power supplies and sometimes even share them. Adding on these 1/4" hex bolts is a necessity to do that.

So of course that means they lose the caps that allow you to screw on these extensions! These pieces allow for the insertion of 2 nuts that can be used to screw onto the power supply and screw the bolt into.

Attach them to the power supply as far as they can go first and then screw in the bolts. Otherwise, it's tough to judge how much thread to leave for the power supply connections.

Prints upright with no supports and even has a stopper ledge for the nuts.

It's a very tight fit, so if you're having trouble, try hitting the piece with a heat gun or blow dryer for a very short amount of time to loosen the plastic. This will also ensure a super tight connection with the nuts.

Enjoy!

This is a design for a 3d-printable ice mold used to make perfect black and tans.
The mold can be filled with water and frozen to make an ice disk with a hole in it. The disc can then be placed into a pint glass, and the Bass or Harp beer is poured in first. It flows through the hole in the ice disk until the glass is filled to the bottom of the disk. The Guinness is then poured on top, and stays separated. The ice melts, and you end up with a perfect pour.
The OD of the disk could be adjusted and the outside edge of the disk could be drafted to match the angle of the pint glass for a better fit.
Using a flexible material would make the ice easier to remove from the mold.

title: Hall-O end-stop bracket for RepRapPro Huxley /w Melzi instructions

description.text: This is a modified version of the original RepRapPro Z end-stop for use with the Hall-Î˜ hall effect sensor. http://reprap.org/wiki/Hall-%CE%98

Install using a 10mm and 30mm screw. Place nuts behind the Hall-O PCB to prevent strain. Hall-O with Melzi electronics
To get the Hall-O end stop working with the Melzi electronics attach a resistor to the base of an NPN transistor and connect the resistor to the digital signal wire from the Hall-O. The other two legs then slot into the Z end-stop connectors on the Melzi board.
Power for the sensor can be taken from the ISP connectors in the bottom right of the board. See attached image.

description.text:
This assembly uses a stepper motor to raise and lower something, for example a small potted plant, or a painting. This thing was made with Tinkercad, edit it online https://www.tinkercad.com/things/4QuS2dBOHn3 . Or edit (or view) the assembled version at https://www.tinkercad.com/things/bGmsS4nAfCj .

It is intended as the hardware for the iotsaMotorServer.

Rafts:

Doesn't Matter

Supports:

Yes

Notes:

Split the file into the constituent parts: 2 parts for the frame, the spindle, the cog and the wire guiding wheel. The white parts (the motor and the microswitch) are for reference only, don't print them.

Be sure to print the spindle and cog with sufficient resolution, so the gears work well enough.

Required extra parts
  • a iotsa server board, see https://github.com/cwi-dis/iotsa.
  • the iotsaMotorServer software, see https://github.com/cwi-dis/iotsaMotorServer.
  • a 28BYJ-48 or equivalent stepper motor.
  • enough wire, that is strong enough (for example 1mm nylon).
  • a microswitch, and some spring wire and/or other bits to construct the end stop.
  • 2 M3 nuts and bolts to attach the stepper motor.
  • 2 M2 nuts and bolts to attach the microswitch.
  • 2 M2 nuts and bolts to attach the iotsaMotorServer board.
Putting things together

Slide the cog over the stepper motor shaft. This may require some sanding, some force, whatever. Use the M3 buts and bolts to attach to the left frame half, do not tighten so the motor can still move.

Slide the guide wheel onto the correct axle (again possibly sanding a bit to ensure it rolls smoothly).

Affix the wire to the spindle. There is a little hole through the spindle and an area where a knot should fit. You may need to drill out the whole a little.

Slide the spindle over the correct axle (note the orientation of the cogs).

Slide the two halves of the frame together.

Attach the iotsaMotorServer board and connect the motor wires.

How to position the microswitch and construct the endstop requires a little creativity. Experiment. The idea is that the endstop is sufficiently below the guide wheel that the microswitch can operate. Note that the microswitch can be mounted in two positions, so if the whole assembly will be deployed upside down (for example affixed to the ceiling) that is possible). You may want to manually operate the switch initially while you are experimenting.

title: Hyperion Case for Google Nexus 5x
license: Creative Commons - Attribution - Non-Commercial - Share Alike

description.text:
I was experimenting with modifying existing STLs, and this was the result. I'd used the original case on my phone for a while, but wanted to see if I could emboss a logo into it, and use multi-color printing to get something even cooler.

The model is funkgerm's case with the embossed Hyperion logo from Borderlands.

Printer Brand:

Prusa

Printer:

Prusa Mk2

Resolution:

.15mm

Infill:

20%

Notes:

To print it similarly, you need to slice it in Slic3r with 20% honeycomb infill, zero bottom layers and two top layers. I printed with three perimeters. To get the color effects, after slicing I used Prusa's Color Print web service to add color changes at 1.1mm (the first solid layer), and again at 8.15mm, where I switched from yellow filament, to black filament, and back again.

I tried to do a similar slicing in Cura and couldn't get it to work. That may be a difference between how the two handle zero-depth top and bottom layers, or it could be I was doing something wrong. But its easy to do in Slic3r.

I've printed this case a couple times, with and without supports. They're kind of a pain to cleanly remove, so if you think your printer can bridge the volume controls, its best without. I got a little sagging with my Prusa MK2, but it did work.

I took the existing STL from the original phone case and imported it into OpenSCAD. After converting an Adobe Illustrator version of the Hyperion logo to SVG with Inkscape, I exported it as DXF and imported that into OpenSCAD. At that point it was just a matter of scaling and positioning the logo, extruding it and then subtracting it from the case object. The depth of the embossing was adjusted to ensure the slicer would leave two layers above it, so I could do the color change.

author: tx2007

title: Daily Equation #2 - Astroid x^(2/3) + y^(2/3) = a

description.text:
This is Day 2 of my collection of printable equations. To see the whole collection, go to: http://www.thingiverse.com/thing:227210 Found a great site of famous & interesting equations: http://www-groups.dcs.st-and.ac.uk/~history/Curves/Curves.html. For today's equation, I picked the Astroid: x^(2/3) + y^(2/3) = a where a = r^2/3 From the site (edited & shortened for clarity): The astroid can be formed by rolling a circle of radius r/4 on the inside of a circle of radius r. It can also be formed as the envelope produced when a line segment is moved with each end on one of a pair of perpendicular axes. It is therefore a glissette. The length of the astroid is 6r and its area is 3ÃÂr^2/8. The astroid was first discussed by Johann Bernoulli in 1691-92. It also appears in Leibniz's correspondence of 1715. It is sometimes called the tetracuspid for the obvious reason that it has four cusps. The astroid only acquired its present name in 1836 in a book published in Vienna. It has been known by various names in the literature, even after 1836, including cubocycloid and paracycle. Details:
  • units are in mm
  • a = 70
  • Range(x) = -50 to 50
  • stl resized to make x axis = 100 mm
    • As always, I'm going to continue to post one equation per day until get bored or people lose interest. If there's a particular equation you'd like to see, leave a comment and I'll give it a shot. Technical Note:
  • The thickness in the y-direction is created by plotting a second curve whose points are a constant distance in the direction perpendicular to the tangent of the first curve. This can create artifacts at regions of rapidly changing slope. However, the lower or inner curve is always correct.
All files can be printed without support. Photos shown were printed on a Replicator 2 and sliced using the standard setting on Makerware.

remixed_from.title: FlyingBear P902 Printed Z Axis supports

description.text:
This is a remix of cederron's excellent design for improved z-axis supports for the FlyingBear P902 printer. The main differences between my design and his original design is that my design has more parts, but my parts can be printed without supports. The purpose of these parts is to simplify the assembly and improve the alignment of the printer's z-axis support rods and z-axis stepper motor and lead screw.

In the original FlyingBear z-axis support design, the two z-axis support rods, and the z-axis stepper and lead screw are all on separate blocks that are very difficult to align. These new parts hold the z-axis support rods and the stepper motor/lead screw assembly in one piece at the top, and one at the bottom, which insures that all three items will be parallel. Since I installed these parts, my z-axis performance improved tremendously, with virtually no z-axis 'banding'.

As part of this upgrade, I replaced the original spiral-flex 5 mm x 8 mm coupling with a multi-piece 'spider'-type flex coupling. This coupling has split-clamp type hubs instead of the setscrew-type hubs of the original coupling. You can find a coupling like this by searching for '5mm x 8mm flex coupling' on Amazon, AliExpress, or eBay.

The files that I uploaded also include '.stp' files of the parts. If you feel the need to change the design or dimensions of these parts, the '.stp' files can be imported into most (if not all) CAD programs. Also, perhaps these parts can 'remixed' so that they can be used on printers of similar design to the FlyingBear.

My most sincere thanks go out to Alex G. Sarriá of the Facebook FlyingBear Users Group for his original Z-axis support design. Alex, if you had not posted your design, I would not have come up with my Z-axis support design.

I hope the community finds this design useful. If you have any comments or questions about these parts, you can post them in the comments section, and I will do my best to answer.

title: Tired of these fidget spinners yet?

description.text:
I've been printing a lot of these spinners lately and decided to make a few of my own. They're very basic as far as design goes, but I added a few things that I felt were missing from other spinners. These spinners are about 0.5mm thicker than the bearings. This is because I sand both flat faces of the spinners and brush with acetone to get a nice finish.

I found I got better spins when the outside bearings were closer to the inside. Also, the more weight to the outside meant more momentum and longer spins. With that in mind I made the borders on the "Circles Spinner Smooth" files thick and got them close to the center bearing. From messing with them a little I found I got the best spin from the Circles spinner with an Amphetamine ceramix silver bearing.

More on bearings:
Sure, the Amphetamine ceramix silver bearing works great, but at $6 each I can't afford to make a bunch for my friends, not to mention I'd still have to get the outer bearings. After a little testing I found I could get similar spins with cheaper hybrid ceramic bearings ($15 for 8) by taking the cheaper rubber dust shields off and cleaning the oil out with brake clean and rubbing alcohol. This works because the oil is really only in there because the bearings were made to carry a load (roller skate bearings), so with no load the oil just gets in the way. I've had mixed results with putting the shields back on or leaving them off as far as slowing the spins goes.

I increased my borders until I had solid infill, Usually around 8 borders. Depending on the printer You'll probably have to increase the scaling of the spinner by at least 1%. I found my happy number was about 1.7% with just a bit of trimming to make the bearings fit snug without cracking the plastic.

Make sure you use the exact same kind of bearing for all of the outside bearings. I was getting vibrations at one point and took me forever to figure out I had use 2 ABEC-5 and 1 ABEC-7 on the outside bearings. To make sure the center bearing went in straight I pushed it in about half way, then flipped the spinner over and pushed the spinner the rest of the way down, using the flat table top to make sure the bearing was even around the rim.

comments.text: "Tolerances are quite tight" is an understatement :P  infill does matter some, unless i just increase my wall count to make it effectively solid :P  I have run into one issue though, very specifically on the "Inner Ring"  I do like how you designed it to overlap, making a modular size cryptex very easy to do, but that 'overlap' part is extremely thin walls.  Thus far I've printed three of them, and all three times those super-thin walls broke, either partially or in whole pieces, while removing the part from my print bed.  It's is worth noting, I am currently printing test pieces at the 'default' size in the STL, so 50 mm outside diameter, ad the sizing is fine, just those really thin inner walls of the inner ring are seem extremely fragile.  My Calipers say they are approximately 0.5 mm, perhaps in the next version this could be increased to 1.0 mm or 1.2 mm?  Being so fragile, i would worry about the durability of the whole cryptex.  nuts and bolts aside, if it were dropped from any mentionable height, they likely wouldn't hold up well.

description.text:
So I posted this on Grabcad, Thought it might be very usefull here, since not everyone is looking on grabcad. It is a zip file from Grabcad, this includes Solidworks 2016 native files, step assy file and X_T assy file. Hope you guys enjoy and use it to make lots and lots of cool prints for me :)

Copy/paste text from Grabcad:
The K8200 is not the cheapest printer out there, and it does not print better than the cheaper printers, but because the use of a lot of standard parts like an aluminum frame it is probably the best customizable printer in the low price section. So I bought one, and I plan to make it a great printer. But for that I needed good CAD files. So I made them, and like to share them with you.

So this is my Solidworks model completely made in Solidworks, detailed to the last washer. I have imported some standard parts from Grabcad, but the Velleman parts are all drawn in Solidworks. I did changed some mates to align parts, these were mostly the simple brackets and the plastic parts, since these where hard to measure.
All other CAD models on the internet where derived from a Sketchup model, which is pretty terrible if you are used to Solidworks models.

Please let me know if there are any errors in the model so I can fix them, it was a lot of work and surely i made some mistakes.
Zip file is a pack and go.
Current bugs:
Missing Z-sensor. The CAD models are there since they are the same as the x-axes.
There is a rogue spring in the extruder.
